            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Leo Giordano\u2019s life has been a study in a single principle: things should work as intended. The son of an Italian-American auto mechanic in San Jose, he grew up surrounded by the smell of motor oil and the satisfying click of a well-seated component. His father didn't just fix cars; he understood them as systems. This tangible, mechanical world captivated Leo, leading him to Cal Poly San Luis Obispo, where a Bachelor's in Mechanical Engineering felt less like an academic pursuit and more like a codification of his deepest instincts.\n\nHis career began in the pre-boom Silicon Valley, designing casings for server racks. While others chased software's ephemeral gold rush, Leo remained grounded in hardware. He found a deep satisfaction in optimizing a production line, in shaving a millimeter off a component to improve thermal dynamics. He survived the dot-com bust because his company made physical objects the internet still needed. This experience cemented his professional philosophy: value stability and tangible results over speculative hype. Through steady, reliable work, he climbed the ladder from junior engineer to his current role as Director of Hardware Manufacturing.\n\nLeo met his wife, Clara, a landscape architect, in his late twenties. Her world of organic, evolving systems perfectly complemented his world of precise, predictable ones. They bought a home in the Sunset District, drawn to the quiet streets and the roar of the nearby ocean, and raised two children who are now in college. This new empty-nest phase is a key turning point, a quiet space that has Leo contemplating what's next for him, personally.\n\nHis daily routine is a familiar circuit. He drives his 6.8 miles from the fog-swept avenues of the Sunset to the industrial grit of the Dogpatch, listening to podcasts on lean manufacturing. At work, he manages people more than machines now, navigating global supply chain issues and mentoring younger engineers. He loves San Francisco for its rugged beauty but is perpetually frustrated by its inefficiencies. His dream isn't to found a startup, but to buy a warehouse space and build the ultimate personal workshop. There, he hopes to restore a vintage Alfa Romeo, a nod to his heritage, and spend his weekends with grease under his fingernails, making something work, just for the love of it."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being nine, his hands too small to properly grip the wrench on a Fiat\u2019s carburetor. His father didn\u2019t scold him for fumbling, just guided his hands. The final turn, the quiet but absolute *click* as the part seated perfectly, was a revelation. It wasn't just fixed; it was *correct*. In that moment, Leo understood the deep, quiet satisfaction of a system restored to its intended state. That sound became his professional and personal north star.\n\n2.\nIt was 2001. The office was a ghost town of abandoned Aeron chairs and unplugged lava lamps. Colleagues who\u2019d boasted of stock options were just gone. But Leo\u2019s desk was piled with schematics for a new server enclosure\u2014a physical object the collapsing digital world still needed. He felt a grim sense of vindication. Hype was vapor, but steel and well-designed airflow were real. It taught him to always trust the tangible, a lesson that defined his entire career.\n\n3.\nOn their first real date, Clara walked him through the Botanical Garden, explaining the chaotic logic of a California native plant bed. He tried to see it as a system, but it was messy and unpredictable. She wasn't designing a machine; she was cultivating a tendency. He, a man of precise tolerances, was completely captivated by her world of beautiful, functional imperfection. He realized then that not all perfect systems had to click into place; some just had to grow.\n\n4.\nHis daughter, frustrated with her wobbly bike wheel, was ready to give up. In their foggy Sunset garage, Leo patiently showed her how to adjust the spokes, explaining tension and balance. He watched her hands slowly learn the feel of the wrench. When she spun the wheel and it ran perfectly true, her face lit up with a shock of understanding. In her pride, he felt a deeper satisfaction than any professional success. He hadn't just fixed a bike; he had passed on the gift of competence.\n\n5.\nHe was stuck on Irving Street, the N-Judah streetcar dead on the tracks ahead. Passengers filed off into the damp fog, defeated. It was a perfect microcosm of San Francisco: a beautiful, century-old system grinding to a halt from sheer neglect. He glanced at his own dashboard, all indicators green. A profound frustration washed over him, solidifying his dream. He didn\u2019t want to fix the city; he just wanted a small garage where, for a few hours, everything would work exactly as it was designed to."
